\begin{eqnarray*}
f_n(x) & = & \frac{x^n}{n!}\exp(-x)\\
S_n(t) & = & \int_t^\infty f_n(x)\;dx
\end{eqnarray*} Conclude that \begin{eqnarray*}S_{n+1}(0) = S_n(0) \end{eqnarray*} for each non-negative integer $n$, and use this observation to conclude that $f_n(x)$ gives us a probability density function on $[0,\infty)$. These densities are known as Gamma densities and $S_n$ is called a survival function .
Conclude that\begin{eqnarray*}
S_{n}(t) = \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{t^k}{k!}\exp(-t)\end{eqnarray*}
Thus the survival function of a Gamma distribution is the distribution function of a Poisson distribution.
